PLANTDESC: Plant 34 cm hoog. Oorspronkelijk hoofdstengel weg, twee stengels vanuit de basis, bloeiende zijtakken boven de 'hoofdtak' uitstekend. Stengelbladen onderaan 52 x 5 mm, gaafrandig of met enkele tanden, tanden c. 0.5 mm lang, bovenaan 46 x 3 mm, gaafrandig, van boven vrij dicht met aanliggende haren, rand gekromde haren. Hoofdjes 4-6 mm breed. Omwindselbladen 2.0-4.6 x 0.4-0.8 mm, behaard, met rode top. Pappus wit. Randbloemen veel, niet uitstekend, linten zeer kort. Buisbloemen 10-14, 0.3-0.4 mm breed. Gemeenschappelijke bloembodem in vrucht 3-4 mm breed. KerngewichtL gem. 4.39.

The maker of the herbarium wrote firstly Bifolium or tweebladt, according to the woodcut in Dodonaeus Cap. 47, pag 260, this refers to the orchid Listera ovata (L.)Br.; Lilium convallium. mey bloomkens.

PLANTDESC: Valeriana communis. Commune valeriane.
NOTES: Page nr. 13A. The roots of this species are still being used as tranquilizer. Clusius cultivated this species and in Dodonaeus there is a whole chapter on Valeriana.; Valeriana communis. Commune valeriane.

PLANTDESC: Valeriana rubae. Redde valeriaan.
NOTES: Page nr. 13B. Specimen left. Still carries the local name 'rode valeriaan' (red valerian).; Valeriana rubae. Redde valeriaan.

NOTES: Page nr. 20B. Specimen right. Osiris is the Egyptian god of the realm of death, husband of Isis and father of Horus. Nowadays Osyris is a genus from Southern Europe belonging to the Santalaceae.; Linaria sive Osris. Wildt vlas.

PLANTDESC: Pentaphllum petreum.
NOTES: Page nr. 22B. This name in the herbarium means: five leaves growing on rocks, referring to its preferred growing places on rocks or other dry habitats. Pentaphyllon was used for all cinquefoils with 5 leaflets. Pentaphyllon vulgaris occurs in the Clusius list, and is now Potentilla reptans L.; Pentaphllum petreum.

NOTES: Page nr. 24B. Specimen (missing).Occurs both in garden of Clusius and in Dodonaeus with same name.; Origanii commune.

PLANTDESC: Origanii creticum.
NOTES: Page nr. 25A. Listed in the garden of Clusius was Origanum heracleoticum. Not found in Dodonaeus.; Origanii creticum.

PLANTDESC: Pseudo Thlaspi.
NOTES: Page nr. 26B.Thlaspi was used for many different Brassicaceae. Listed by Clusius as 'grijskruid' was Thlaspi clypeatum.; Pseudo Thlaspi.

PLANTDESC: Agrimonium. agrimonie.
NOTES: Page nr. 27B.This specimen can refer to both local agrimony species. A. procera (fragrant agrimony) was also cultivated. It is not possible to identify this specimen to species level.; Agrimonium. agrimonie.

PLANTDESC: Oleander. oleanderboom.
NOTES: Page nr. 28B. This very poisonous plant, growing originally along rivers near the Mediterranean Sea, was one of the first cultivated as medicinal plant. Clusius used Nerion.; Oleander. oleanderboom.

PLANTDESC: Lentiscus.
NOTES: Page nr. 29B. Specimen no longer present. In southern Europe a source of mastic gum.; Lentiscus.

PLANTDESC: Alchimilla Pes leonis. Lewen voet.
NOTES: Page nr. 31B.There is detached material that fits this page. Exact identification of the material is not possible, due to the difficult taxonomy of Alchemilla. The alchemists of the Middle Ages believed that dew gathered from the leaves of this genus had magical properties and could be used to make precious metals.; Alchimilla Pes leonis. Lewen voet.

PLANTDESC: Aconitum lycoctonum. Blauwe wolfswortele.
NOTES: Page nr. 32B. Aconitum lycoctonumnormally refers to the yellowA. vulpariaReichenb. but here in the herbarium the blue species is attached and referred to.; Aconitum lycoctonum. Blauwe wolfswortele.

PLANTDESC: Arabis sive Draba.
NOTES: Page nr. 34B. Cad did not know which Brassicaceae this was. Both Arabis and Draba were used by Clusius for quite some Brassicaceae.; Arabis sive Draba.

NOTES: Page nr. 36B. All large-flowered plants growing along streams and rivers were called Lysimachium. Only one genus retained this name. On the titlepage of Dodonaeus there is an illustration of a loosestrife. He wrote: 'het heeft sijnen naem gecregen van sijnen eersten ervinder Lysimachus, den sonne van Agothocles' (it got its name from the person who found it first: Lysimachus, son of Agothocles).; Lysimachium verum. Geel wederick.

NOTES: Page nr. 39B. The local name 'Hoenderbeet' is currently used for Lamium amplexicaule L. Dodonaeus gives an illustration of Veronica hederifolia L. to go with 'Hoenderbeet'. So probably Cad made a misidentification.; Elatine. Hoenderbeet.

NOTES: Page nr. 40B.; Centaurium minus. Clein Santorie.

PLANTDESC: Althaea.
NOTES: Page nr. 42B. The roots were soaked in wine and used against internal bleedings and stomach pains. Soaked in fresh milk it was supposed to cure coughs.; Althaea.

PLANTDESC: Millefolium rubeum.
NOTES: Page nr. 43B. This was probably a reddish tinged specimen of Millefolium, occurring in lawns often in this form.; Millefolium rubeum.

PLANTDESC: Smilax aspera. stekende winde.
NOTES: Page nr. 44B. Specimen (missing). Although the specimen is missing, the inprint is clear enough for a positive identification.; Smilax aspera. stekende winde.

NOTES: Page nr. 45B. Specimen right (original is missing).Solidago virgaurea (echte guldenroede, Golden rod) should have been attached here, but is missing . In its place, attached with a pin, is a piece of Umbilicus rupestris.; Virga aurea. guldenroede.

PLANTDESC: Conyza media.
NOTES: Page nr. 47B. The name Conyza is mostly used for alant (Inula spp.), but this species looks much alike. According to Dodonaeus, it was used for many different illnesses, like falling disease, yellow fever, menstrual pain, insect bites, flees, and inflammation, depending on the solution liquid and whether it was taken in- or externally.; Conyza media.

PLANTDESC: Mentastrum. witte water munte.
NOTES: Page nr. 48B. Mentastrum is used in Dodonaeus for 'Roode water munte', Mentha aquatica L. (Water mint).; Mentastrum. witte water munte.
Page nr. 49B. ???? No info, most of the specimen is no longer present.

PLANTDESC: Tithymalus characias. Wolfs melck.
NOTES: Page nr. 51A. There has been a mix up of Euphorbia characias L. and E. cyparissias L. The first is missing on page 51B. The woodcuts in Dodonaeus to go with Tithymalus characias and Tithymalus dendroides indicate a different spurge species than the one attached in this herbarium. The woodcut of 'Wolfsmelck manneken' indicates Euphorbia amygdaloides L.; Tithymalus characias. Wolfs melck.

PLANTDESC: Tithmalus cparissias.
NOTES: Page nr. 51B. Upper specimen (missing).See page 51A, due to the fact that this species is already attached on the formerpage, perhaps a specimen of E. characias L. was attached here.; Tithmalus cparissias.

PLANTDESC: Tithymalus myrsinites.
NOTES: Page nr. 51B. Specimen left below. Originating from Northern Africa upto Central Asia. A creeping, hardy species.; Tithymalus myrsinites.

PLANTDESC: Tithymaly Dandroides.
NOTES: Page nr. 51B. Specimen right below. This is a very unusual cultivated plant from the Mediterranean and Cyprus. The woodcut and description in Dodonaeus of 'croonkens cruyt' depicts E. heliosopia L.; Tithymaly Dandroides.

PLANTDESC: Scordium verum. Water loock.
NOTES: Page nr. 52B. This specimen has deeper lobed leaves that the ones archived in the Utrecht herbarium. Clusius used Scordium for all Teucrium spp.; Scordium verum. Water loock.

PLANTDESC: Lotus urbana. seven getyden crut.
NOTES: Page nr. 53B.This species was/is cultivated for fodder and alfalfa. It escapes easily from cultivation, hence 'urbana'. Lotus was used for different types of wild legumes. According to Dodonaeus it 's local name was derived ' om dattet suen mael tsdaechs snen rueck verliest ende wedercrght als gheset es' (because it is told that this herb looses and regains its sent seven times a day). Lucerne was used to cure swellings and it was applied together with honey to reduce scar tissue. It would help clean out the eyes and it would be able to cure fresh wounds.; Lotus urbana. seven getyden crut.

PLANTDESC: Cyclaminus. Verckens broot.
NOTES: Page nr. 54B.The bulbs of this species, occurring in the wild till northern France, were in earlier times used as pig fodder, e.g. at the hunt for truffles.; Cyclaminus. Verckens broot.

PLANTDESC: Hermodactili.
NOTES: Page nr. 55B.According to Dodonaeus, 'Hermodactilen' were 'ghebruyckt iaghen af duer den camerganck die taeye slijmactighe fluymen die selue uit den veerden leden halende / ende sn seer sonderlinghe tseghen dat fledercn ende sciatica ende allen pijne der leden gebruyckt' (used to loosen very tough phlegm / used especially for spine, shoulder and pelvis disorders and all other pains in the limbs). Although there are some warnings for the use of this very poisonous and cancerous plant 'verbrant die maghe ende quetst die inwendighe leden alzoo dat ten laetsten bloedighen camerganck volght ende alzoo dooder den mensche' (it burns the stomach and hurts the inner parts in such a manner that it results in bloody bowels and in this way can also be a killer). This can be prevented by adding 'Gengebeer oft lanck peper / saet van Anijs oft Comijn ende wat Mastix' (Ginger ale (?) or long pepper / aniseed or cumin and some Mastix (Pistacia lentiscus, page 29B). At present, Hermodactylus is being used for an Iridaceae: Hermodactylus tuberosus (L.) Mill.; Hermodactili.

PLANTDESC: Polium montanum verum.
NOTES: Page nr. 56B.; Polium montanum verum.
Page nr. 57B. Very hard to identify Boraginaceae, probably an Anchusa. In alphabetical Index both Heliotropium maius and H. minus direct to this page.

PLANTDESC: Eupatorium mesue flore albo.
NOTES: Page nr. 58B. Specimen left. Clusius used another name. Eupatorium is included in the Libri picturati from the same period.; Eupatorium mesue flore albo.

PLANTDESC: Eupatorium mesue flo citrino.
NOTES: Page nr. 58B. Specimen right.; Eupatorium mesue flo citrino.

PLANTDESC: Soldonella.
NOTES: Page nr. 59B. According to Dodonaeus it was used against oedema and liver diseases. It had to be mixed with oil or grease and either taken as a drink or powder. The latter method was damaging for the stomach.; Soldonella.

PLANTDESC: Creta marina. Crithmum.
NOTES: Page nr. 60A. This plant was used agains menstrual pains and yellow fever. The two specimen in the herbarium were probably collected in the wild; this species is very hard to cultivate.; Creta marina. Crithmum.

SPECIES: Lilium bulbiferum L. var. croceum (Chaix) Pers.
PLANTDESC: Lilium rufum.
NOTES: Page nr. 60B.This species used to grow in fields with rye in the northern part of the Netherlands, but it origin is in Germany. Since the 17th century this species is the symbol of the Dutch Royal Family and is called 'oranjelelie' (orange lily).; Lilium rufum.

PLANTDESC: Halicacabus. Criecken van ouer zee.
NOTES: Page nr. 62A.This plant came into early cultivation in Europe. Probably originating from Eastern Asia and an early introduction by the VOC or arrived in Western Europe via the silk route. The brightly colored lanterns stay attached a long time and the berries contain alkaloids. This species reproduces via creeping rhizomes and was found in the wild already in 1554. According to Dodonaeus 'in soomighe bosschen ende bij die haghen in neere vochtschtighe plaetsen ende worden oock vele in die houen gheplant' (in some forests and near hedges in lowlying wet sites and it is also cultivated).; Halicacabus. Criecken van ouer zee.

PLANTDESC: Halicacabus peregrinus. Vremde criecken van ouer zee.
NOTES: Page nr. 62B. Originally from Central America. This species is cultivated due to its curious balloon shaped fruits, with black seeds that carry a heart-shaped pattern. The plants carry tendrils in the inflorescence, a characteristic for many Sapindaceae. Dodonaeus was not sure where to place this plant, he was able to place the other 'criecken van ouer see' (herb from the other side of the ocean) near to the 'Nascaye' (nightshades), but Cardiospermum belongs to a 'ander vremd gheslacht' (another strange genus).; Halicacabus peregrinus. Vremde criecken van ouer zee.

PLANTDESC: Paeonia femina.
NOTES: Page nr. 63B. Specimen left. The 'female' peony was much more used for medicinal purposes than the male Paeonia mascula (L.) Mill. Unfortionately, the male one is missing.; Paeonia femina.

PLANTDESC: Paeonia mascula.
NOTES: Page nr. 63B. Specimen right (missing).The 'female' peony was much more used for medicinal purposes than the male Paeonia mascula (L.) Mill. Unfortionately, the male one is missing.; Paeonia mascula.

PLANTDESC: Doronicum Romanum.
NOTES: Page nr. 64B.; Doronicum Romanum.

PLANTDESC: Buphthalmum sive Oculus bonis.
NOTES: Page nr. 65B. Specimen left. Buphthalmus is the greek word for bulls eye. The roots were sometimes sold by pharmacists as Helleboris niger, causing quite some misunderstandings. The flowers are pulverized together with oil to make a salve that softened hard swellings.; Buphthalmum sive Oculus bonis.

PLANTDESC: Rhodiaradix.
NOTES: Page nr. 65B. Specimen right. This species originates from the mountains of Middle Europe and carries much smaller leaves than the at present cultivated form originating from Northern Europe. Dodonaeus wrote: 'Roosewortel wast in Macedonien ende in Hungarien. Hier te lande wordt zy in der cruytliefhebbers houen gheplant.....maer selden brengt zy bloemen voort' (This species occurs in Macedonien and Hungary. Here in this country it is kept by herblovers....but it flowers rarely). Hence, the sterile state of the specimen in the herbarium . The broken root smells like roses and would lessen headaches.; Rhodiaradix.

PLANTDESC: Narcissus Tempestinus.
NOTES: Page nr. 66A. Left specimen. Dodonaeus wrote a beautiful (long) piece on the 'oirsake sijns naems' (origin of the name), hopefully the book will become online shortly, for an update of the progress click here.; Narcissus Tempestinus.
Page nr. 66A. Right specimen.

PLANTDESC: Hepatica trinistas Ital.
NOTES: Page nr. 66B. This species was used to clean the liver, due to the likeness of the leaves with a pig's liver. It was supposed that the human liver would look alike and that those plants resembling a certain organ would help cure it.; Hepatica trinistas Ital.

PLANTDESC: Stachs. rieckende andoren.
NOTES: Page nr. 67B.Clusius called this species Stachys odora.; Stachs. rieckende andoren.

PLANTDESC: Verbascum syluestre.
NOTES: Page nr. 68B. Specimen left. Dodonaeus wrote: 'Wildt wollecruyt ....den Sauien seer ghelijck....aen die Maelruwe van verwen geel' ( Wild woolly herb....looks like Salvia .....or like a malrove (Marrubium vulgare) with yellow flowers.; Verbascum syluestre.

PLANTDESC: Verbascutum odoratum. Welrieckende sluetelbloemen.
NOTES: Page nr. 68B. Specimen right. Both species are given in Dodonaeus, but in this book more Verbascu(tu)m are described.; Verbascutum odoratum. Welrieckende sluetelbloemen.

PLANTDESC: Genista humilis. Ackerbrem.
NOTES: Page nr. 70B.; Genista humilis. Ackerbrem.

PLANTDESC: Sesamoides Mathioli minor.
NOTES: Page nr. 72A.Clusius called this species Stachys odora.; Sesamoides Mathioli minor.
Page nr. 72B.
Page nr. 73B.

PLANTDESC: Cerinthe Plin.

PLANTDESC: Clematidis alterius altera species.
NOTES: Page nr. 77A.Dodonaeus wrote that also other species of Clematis were identified as this one: 'Noch vindt men een ander gheslacht van Winde / dat oock van sommighen voor een Clematis altera ghehouden wordt / .. Die bloemen sijn groot / in vieren ghesneden / van verwe blauw /..' (there is also another genus that climbs / that some people also call C. altera / the flowers are big / divided in 4/ and with a bleu color). This description can apply to a blue form of C. viticella L. or C. alpina (L.) Mill. C. montana Buch.-Ham. ex DC originates from East Asia and arrived much later in Europe.; Clematidis alterius altera species.

PLANTDESC: Agnus castus Vitex. Schafmulle.
NOTES: Page nr. 80B.The German local name can indicate that Cad received this plant from Germany or via a German order. This species was used by monks to keep to celibacy. According to Dodonaeus: 'een seer sonderlinghe medecne ende remedie voer den ghenen die in reynichheyt leuen willen / want hij wederstaet alle oncuysliche lusten ende begheerte', (a very perculiar medicine and treatment for those who want to live in purity / because he will resist all obscene lust and longings). Hence, the local names. Dodonaeus also wrote: 'dat reysende luyden / die daeraf een tacxken ouer huer draghen / niet moede en worden nog geen versmerthheyten crijghen' (travelling people / who carry a branch therefrom / do not get tired or pains).; Agnus castus Vitex. PLANTDESC: Cistus ladanifera, herba ladanum.

The name seems to refer to a Cistus without ladanum (a medicinal resin). This could be an indication of a parasitic infection by Cytinus hypocistis L. This Rafflesiaceae only grows on white-flowered Cistus species. Cytinus ruber L. grows only on redflowered species (Blamey & Grey-Wilson, 1993). Dodonaeus wrote: 'Bij de wortelen van desen Cistus / wordt in die landen daer hy van selfs groeyet geuonden sekere aenwassinghe / van verwen som geel / som wit / som groen / ende daer uit wordt sap ghedruckt / dat in die Apotheke ghebruyckt wordt'...'Dat bij die wortelen van desen Cistus groeyet wordt gheheeten in Griecx Hypocisthis......ende Cytinus / in die apothkene Hypoquistidos' (at the roots of this Cistus / in the countries of origin can special growths be found / sometimes yellow / soemtimes white / sometimes green /from which juice is being pressed / which is used in the pharmacy.....That what is grows at the roots of this Cistus is called in Greek Hypocisthis .... and Cytinus / in the pharmacy Hypoquistidos.; Cistus ladanifera, herba ladanum.
